In JavaScript, there are two types of execution: synchronous and asynchronous. Each has its own advantages based on the task you're performing.

Synchronous Execution is when code blocks execute one after another, from top to bottom in a sequential order. This means that each line of code must finish executing before moving onto the next line. If an operation takes time (like reading a large file or making a network request), it will freeze your program until the operation completes. 

Here's an example of synchronous execution:
```javascript
console.log("Start");
console.log("This code is running sequentially");
console.log("End");
```
In this case, each line waits for its predecessor to finish before executing. "Start" is printed first, then the second message, and finally "End". 

Asynchronous Execution on the other hand allows code execution to continue even if a time-consuming operation is in progress. This prevents the program from freezing while it waits for the task to complete. Instead, JavaScript uses callback functions which are executed when the asynchronous tasks finishes its work. 

Here's an example of asynchronous execution using setTimeout:
```javascript
console.log("Start");
setTimeout(function() {
    console.log("Asynchronous task has finished");
}, 2000); //This will wait for 2 seconds before executing the callback function
console.log("End");
```
In this example, "Start" is printed immediately followed by "End". Then after a delay of two seconds (set in setTimeout), "Asynchronous task has finished" is printed. Even though there's a time gap between these lines, it doesn't affect the flow of the program because JavaScript handles other tasks during this wait period. 

The concept of asynchronous execution is vital for handling tasks that take long periods to complete like network requests or file operations without freezing your application. This is why understanding and using callbacks effectively becomes an essential part of coding in JavaScript, especially when dealing with APIs and server-side programming where the majority of work tends to be I/O bound rather than CPU bound.

The requirements for using an electronic signature in place of a wet ink signature vary from state to state. In the case of Maine, according to their Electronic Signature Law (10 MRS §289-A) which follows the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (UETA), you may use an electronic signature for filing a Certificate of Amendment provided that:

1. The parties involved have consented to using electronic signatures, and it is reasonable to expect they would receive such consent in the ordinary course of business;
2. There must be a reliable method used by each party to verify their identity during the process of signing electronically;
3. The electronic signature must adequately indicate that the parties intended to authenticate the document or transaction; and, 
4. You should retain an accurate and unalterable copy of the signed document for future reference and audit purposes.

Therefore, as long as these conditions are met, you can use electronic signatures in Maine for filing a Certificate of Amendment. However, it is always recommended to check with your local government or legal advisors before relying on an electronic signature process.

